HANTAVIRUS UPDATE - AMERICAS (15): USA (VIRGINIA), NOT
******************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 1 May 2014
Source: The Roanoke Times [edited]
http://www.roanoke.com/community/the_burgs/rare-combination-of-flu-and-strep-blamed-for-pulaski-county/article_b11e22fa-d0ad-11e3-8801-0017a43b2370.html?mode=jqm


The illness that hospitalized a Snowville family of 5, killing 2, was not hantavirus as previously suspected, according to health officials.

Instead, it was a combination of 2 common and treatable illnesses, influenza type B and streptococcus Group A, that together claimed the lives of a woman and her 14-year-old daughter on 25 Apr 2014. Individually, neither the flu nor strep cause tremendous concern, but together they are "extremely, extremely rare and serious," New River Health District Director Molly O'Dell said. During a media teleconference on Wed 30 Apr 2014, O'Dell said both the flu and strep are circulating in the region, but there doesn't seem to be any threat to the community because it is so rare to become infected with both simultaneously.

The health department has not made an official cause of death finding -- that can come only from the medical examiner's office -- but health officials on the call talked about how the combination of flu and strep could be deadly. Doctors have not identified anyone else in the area who has been co-infected, O'Dell said.

No one in the family had received a flu shot, and all 5 members tested positive for the flu and showed signs of strep. It's impossible to know where they picked it up or whether they contracted both at the same time, O'Dell said. "A lot of times, what we'll say in medicine is just because you have one thing doesn't mean you can't have another, a 2nd thing," she said. "So if someone gets influenza, it certainly makes them more vulnerable to pick up bacterial infections."

The kind of co-infection that struck the family is so rare that it hasn't been studied by scientists, and only about 10 cases have ever been reported in all the medical literature that Tom Kerkering, Carilion's chief of infectious diseases, could find. "I've been doing infectious diseases for 35 years. This is the 1st time I've seen the combination," Kerkering said during the teleconference.

The family and Pulaski County's emergency services director previously suspected the family had contracted a hantavirus [infection], a rare and sometimes fatal virus passed to humans through rodent feces and urine. The women died about 2 weeks after they began cleaning out a mouse-infested mobile home that they planned to give to the family of a boyfriend who lives in a homeless shelter.

The rest of the family, the father, 2 younger children, and the boyfriend, were also hospitalized but recovered and were released.

[Byline: Jacob Demmitt]

